<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10109c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10109c">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10109c"> 109(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lover&apos;s initials in / snail tracks (1.v.924)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><b>May Day Festivities and Traditions / Echoes of Pagan Worship</b> May Eve and <mark>May Day</mark> were once the great feasts of Baal, the sun-god, when his fires were lit on the hillsides and children and cattle were passed through them for purification. <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> The maidens went forth early that day to seek <mark>the initials of their future husbands in snail-tracks</mark>. If on this journey a white snail was first met it meant good fortune, but a black snail seen first was a harbinger of death. <small> <a name="II30apr24" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#II30apr24"><cite title="source">Irish Independent</cite></a> (30 April 1924) 6/5</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
